tText>Internet of Things (IoT) is a disruptive technology that fuel the development of connected cyber-physical systems (CPS) devices leading into the Industry 4.0 revolution with smart applications across diverse domains from robotics and manufacturing, transportation and logistics, healthcare, environmental/cities management etc. Alongside the growth of these infrastructures, the volume and variety of cyberattacks on such critical infrastructures has increased. For instance, the Mirai botnet was able to infect more than 2.5 million IoT devices and consequently used to launch a successful Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS ) attack on the Domain Name Service (DNS) provider Dyn. The latest botnet threats such as those posed by the incarnation of Mirai botnet known as Reaper, exploiting vulnerabilities and security flaws in the pre-installed firmware of IoT/CPS connected devices. These attack exemplify the susceptibility of connected devices to security threats as well as providing a glimpse into the devastation of successful attempts in bringing down smart critical infrastructures. In this context, we aim to develop a security platform called Cyber Monitoring and Defence (CyMonD) for IoT/CPS, with cutting edge capabilities tasked to perform an active periodic monitoring, and defending against the compromised connected devices. The technological solution of CyMonD would have the ability to identify and quarantine connected devices that are hijacked by unauthorised access through any means of security and vulnerabilities exploitation, of which then, compromised them with malicious codes. The solution is envisaged to be lightweight as there is no data traffic analysis, expandable while more connected devices are added, scalable along the growth of connected devices deployments, effective against ?Zero Day? attack, and has a provision to cure compromised devices by restoring to the known-good status. Using CyMonD, users/operators can be assured that the deployed connected devices are in-service with its system integrity intact.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2018-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/E18E2F0F-AC7D-4E02-9559-669F7C8FEC74"><gtr:id>E18E2F0F-AC7D-4E02-9559-669F7C8FEC74</gtr:id><gtr:name>Innovate UK</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2018-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>9661</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">133568</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>D05BC2E0-0345-4A3F-8C3F-775BC42A0819</gtr:id><gtr:text>Unclassified</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>